+## Task Info Panel
+
+The persistent wide-terminal footer is `[Tab] switch  [Enter] action  [n] new  [/] filter  [?] help  [i] info  [q] quit`. Narrow terminals retain the existing single-line width clamp and show an ellipsis when the full 79-character legend does not fit.
+
+Pressing `i` on a selected task in the right pane captures one immutable snapshot and replaces the two-pane grid for that frame. Every panel shows:
+
+- the task slug and current stage;
+- the `created_at` value and captured `original_text` from `idea.md`;
+- the absolute task-folder path; and
+- the absolute path of the most recently modified regular `*.log` in the [[modules/task]] task log directory, or `(none)` when no task log exists.
+
+The optional final section follows the selected row's stage:
+
+| Stage | Extra section |
+|---|---|
+| `1-inbox` | none |
+| `2-brainstorm` | bounded contents of `brainstorm.md` |
+| `3-plan` | bounded contents of `plan.md` |
+| `4-execute` | bounded tail of the newest regular `execute-*.log`; a newer non-execute log can still be the common latest-log path without becoming execute output |
+
+The panel reads each artifact once when it opens, scrubs invalid UTF-8 and terminal control bytes, then renders only the captured model value. Reads are byte-bounded and optional artifacts fail soft. The `idea.md` read budget accounts for four-byte UTF-8 plus YAML block-scalar overhead before applying the 64 Ki-character `original_text` cap, so a valid bounded idea still includes its closing frontmatter delimiter. Frontmatter is rejected before `YAML.safe_load` when collection nesting exceeds 64 levels, preventing Psych's recursive object visitor from overflowing the TUI stack. Task logs are enumerated with literal directory entries (project paths containing glob metacharacters remain valid), and a selected log's device/inode identity is revalidated on the open descriptor before its path or contents enter the snapshot. A rotated/replaced file therefore becomes `(none)` instead of mixing stale discovery metadata with replacement content. Oversized execute logs keep useful captured suffix content after the leading `...` marker, including when the captured suffix's only newline is its final byte.
+
+Rendering is bounded by both terminal dimensions: wrapping stops after the current height budget, scans only a height/width-proportional prefix of each bounded body, and measures grapheme clusters through a pure-Ruby terminal-width path so CJK and emoji cannot escape the declared frame without paying a native bridge call per cluster. A truncated scan is itself treated as overflow, including for unusually byte-heavy ZWJ or combining-mark graphemes. Content that exceeds the current frame ends with a visible `...`, or `…` when only one terminal cell is available; this mode does not scroll, page, search, or launch an external viewer.
+
+`q`, `Esc`, and `i` close the panel and restore the selected task identity, scope, filter, and pane focus. Snapshot polls locate the selection by project name plus slug, so removal of an earlier row can move its coordinates without making the close gesture select the next task. Every other key is a no-op while it is open. Opening and closing never dispatches a workflow, changes stages or markers, starts a process, calls the network, or performs a git operation. The existing `?` help-overlay content is outside this mode's behavior and remains unchanged.
+
 Findings triage is no longer an in-TUI mode. Use `hive findings`, `hive accept-finding`, and `hive reject-finding` directly from a shell or coding agent; legacy `EXECUTE_WAITING findings_count` rows surface as `recover_execute` and point at `hive findings` from status JSON (see [[commands/findings]]). In red-status detail mode, `Enter` runs hive's automated recovery for the task and closes the detail screen (rows with no auto-recovery recipe surface a refusal flash that names `Open in agent` as the manual fallback before closing), `o` opens the task in the project's configured development agent and closes the detail screen, and `q` / `Esc` returns to the grid. The help overlay groups bindings by mode for the disambiguation.
 
 ## New Idea Prompt Editing
